\title{AisStream: Live Vessel-Tracking Client for AISStream.io}
\description{
An event-driven client for the \href{https://aisstream.io}{AISStream.io} live AIS
(vessel-tracking) WebSocket feed, built on \link[connectcore:StreamClient]{connectcore::StreamClient}. You
construct it with an API key and one or more bounding boxes (plus optional MMSI /
message-type filters), register handlers with \verb{$on(event, handler)} exactly as in
Node's \code{ws.on(...)}, then \verb{$run()} to pump the loop. The 3-second subscribe
deadline, reconnect-and-resubscribe, keepalive, and a silence watchdog are all
inherited.
\subsection{The hot path is parse-free (this is non-negotiable)}{

AISStream monitors your TCP read queue and \strong{closes the connection if it backs
up} — at the whole-world firehose (~300 msg/s) a per-message JSON parse cannot
keep up. So \code{.dispatch()} does \strong{no} parsing on the data path: it emits the raw
string under \code{"message"}, and the \emph{only} inspection is a cheap \code{startsWith()}
prefix check to route error frames (\code{{"error": ...}}) to the \code{"error"} event
instead. Parse in your own handler if you must, but for the firehose the proven
pattern is \code{\link[=ndjson_sink]{ndjson_sink()}} — \verb{$on("message", ndjson_sink(dir))} (append raw frames
now, parse offline later with \code{\link[=parse_ais]{parse_ais()}}).
}

\subsection{Bounding boxes}{

Each box is two opposite \verb{[lat, lon]} corners. Pass them either as named lists —
\code{list(min_lat =, min_lon =, max_lat =, max_lon =)} (the JS-object style) — or as
raw nested corners \code{list(c(lat1, lon1), c(lat2, lon2))}; both normalise to
AISStream's \verb{[[min_lat, min_lon], [max_lat, max_lon]]}. Latitudes are validated to
\verb{[-90, 90]}, longitudes to \verb{[-180, 180]}. Boxes may overlap.
}
}
